'''Lourdes College''' is a independent, [[private university|private]], [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]] [[university]] in [[Sylvania, Ohio]], {{convert|10|mi|km}} northwest of [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]]. The [[liberal-arts]] institution opened in 1958 as Lourdes Junior College to educate sisters of the Franciscan community.

Rooted in the Catholic [[Franciscan|Franciscan tradition]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Lourdes College|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/AboutLourdes/MissionMinistry/FranciscanValues.aspx|title=Franciscan tradition|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Lourdes offers [[baccalaureate degree]] programs in the arts, business, education, nursing, sciences and social work as well as [[master's degree|graduate degrees]] in education, nursing, organizational leadership and theology. The institution also offers pre-professional programs such as art therapy, engineering, law, medicine, occupational therapy, physical therapy and veterinary science. It is classified as a [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education#Master<U+2019>s Colleges and Universities|Master<U+2019>s university]] by the [[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]].<ref name="carnegie">{{cite web|url=http://classifications.carnegiefoundation.org/lookup_listings/view_institution.php?unit_id=203757&start_page=institution.php&clq=%7B%22ipug2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ipgrad2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22enrprofile2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ugprfile2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22sizeset2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22basic2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22eng2005_ids%22%3A%22%22%2C%22search_string%22%3A%22Lourdes+College%22%2C%22level%22%3A%22%22%2C%22control%22%3A%22%22%2C%22accred%22%3A%22%22%2C%22state%22%3A%22%22%2C%22region%22%3A%22%22%2C%22urbanicity%22%3A%22%22%2C%22womens%22%3A%22%22%2C%22hbcu%22%3A%22%22%2C%22hsi%22%3A%22%22%2C%22tribal%22%3A%22%22%2C%22msi%22%3A%22%22%2C%22landgrant%22%3A%22%22%2C%22coplac%22%3A%22%22%2C%22urban%22%3A%22%22%7D|title=Carnegie Foundation Classification - Bellarmine University|publisher=[[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching|Carnegie Foundation]]|year=2008-2010|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Lourdes has been named a <U+201C>Best in the Midwest<U+201D> college by the [[Princeton Review]] for seven consecutive years from 2004-2011.<ref name="best">{{cite news|last=Staff|work=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Toledo|Catholic Chronicle]]|url=http://www.catholicchronicle.org/index.php/Saint-Luke-Deanery/lourdes-college-named-among-best-in-nation.html|title=Lourdes College named among best in nation|date=August 24, 2010|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref>

Lourdes currently has an enrollment of about 2,600 students. The college provides a variety of social, recreational and educational activities to further enrich students<U+2019> lives. From music concerts and educational lectures to intramural sports, students will find something for every interest. Service and volunteering is encouraged and the college provides many opportunities for experience, such as [[Habitat for Humanity]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Lourdes College|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/AboutLourdes/MissionMinistry/CampusMinistry.aspx|title=Department of Mission & Ministry|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> The college began intercollegiate athletics program in 2010 and competes in the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) in the [[Wolverine-Hoosier Athletic Conference]].<ref name="whac">{{cite news|last=VanOchten|first=Brian|work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]]|url=http://www.mlive.com/smallcolleges/grandrapids/index.ssf/2011/03/lourdes_college_approved_as_ne.html|title=Lourdes College approved as new WHAC member|date=March 30, 2011|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref>

==History==
=== Founding and early history ===
In the early 1900s Mother Adelaide Sandusky lead a group of sisters from the [[Sisters of Saint Francis of Rochester, Minnesota]] to [[Northwest Ohio]] and became known as the [[Sisters of St. Francis of Sylvania, Ohio]].<ref name="sisters">{{cite web|work=Sisters of St. Francis of Sylvania, Ohio|url=http://www.fscsylvania.org/sisters.html|title=History of the Sisters of St. Francis of Sylvania, Ohio|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> The Sisters began educating students in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Toledo|Toledo Diocese]].<ref name="timeline">{{cite web|work=Lourdes College|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/AboutLourdes/HistoryoftheCollege/LourdesCollegeTimeline.aspx|title=Timeline of Lourdes College|publisher=|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Soon after arriving in Toledo they established Provincialate High School to prepare the Sisters for education and healthcare careers. In 1917 the group purchased {{convert|89|acre|km2|adj=on}} of farmland in Sylvania.<ref name="timeline"/> Following the [[Great Depression]] in the early 1940s the property became the location for an extension campus of the [[College of Saint Teresa]].<ref name="history">{{cite web|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/AboutLourdes/HistoryoftheCollege.aspx|title=History of Lourdes College|publisher=Lourdes College|accessdate=2011-1-17}}</ref>

Lourdes received its certificate of authorization from the [[Ohio State Board of Education]] in January, 1958, at which time it became known as Lourdes Junior College.<ref name="timeline"/><ref name="history"/> Although originally established to educate sisters of the Franciscan community, the college became fully accredited in 1964 and began to admit [[lay]] women in 1969 and it became known as Lourdes College in 1973 after the college began offering four-year degrees.<ref name="timeline"/> In 1975 men were admitted for the first time in the school's history.<ref name="history"/>

In 1982, the [[Ohio Board of Regents]] authorized Lourdes College to grant two baccalaureate degrees, the Bachelor of Individualized Studies and the Bachelor of Arts in Religious Studies.<ref name="timeline"/> In 1986, Lourdes was authorized to add the Bachelor of Arts, with seven majors, and [[Bachelor of Science in Nursing]] (B.S.N.).<ref name="timeline"/> In 2002, graduate programs at Lourdes were approved by the Ohio Board of Regents and accredited by the North Central Association.<ref name="timeline"/> The college later expanded the graduate programs, adding a Master of Organizational Leadership, Master of Education, Master of Arts in Theology, and Master of Science in Nursing programs.<ref name="timeline"/>

=== Recent history ===
Student enrollment reached an all-time high of 2,035 during the 2006-07 academic year and the college continues to see new all-time enrollment records.<ref name="timeline"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Hoffmanwork|first=H.|work=Lourdes College|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/Newsroom/PressReleases/tabid/764/EntryId/1266/Lourdes-posts-12-increase-in-spring-enrollment.aspx|title=Lourdes posts 12% increase in spring enrollment|date=January 28, 2011|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> To keep up with the needs of a growing student body, Lourdes commenced construction of a new academic building in October 2006. The new building, composed of Delp Hall and McAlear Hall, opened in 2007. Delp Hall, which was designed to be environmentally friendly, houses the Ebeid Center and the WIN Center.<ref name="timeline"/> The Ebeid Center was designed by students for students and offers a place to gather, study, watch TV, play games or put on small stage performances. The WIN Center offers an environment an environment focused on student success and retention. The Center has groups study rooms, computer labs and academic support to all Lourdes students in good standing. McAlear Hall features additional classrooms, faculty offices, and space for finance and information technology operations.<ref name="timeline"/>

In fall 2007, Lourdes announced plans to expand its nursing program through a partnership with [[Promedica Health System]], and classes began at [[The Toledo Hospital]] in January 2008.<ref name="timeline"/> A year later, the Lourdes School of Nursing launched a new Operating Room First Assistant program, followed shortly by the introduction of the Registered Nurse (RN) to Master of Science in Nursing (MSN).<ref name="timeline"/> In 2009 The [[Chronicle of Higher Education]] named Lourdes one of the "Top 10 Places to Work For.<U+201D><ref name="timeline"/> The college initiated a Pre-Engineering program in partnership with the [[University of Detroit Mercy]] and added a new  Master of Arts in Theology degree program.<ref name="timeline"/> 

Although predominately commuter campus, in 2010 Lourdes opened the new Lourdes Commons student housing complex after renovating the Wickford Woods apartments located next to the main campus.<ref>{{cite news|last=Staff|work=[[WTVG]]|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wtvg/story?section=news/local&id=7368567|title=Lourdes College unveils plans for student housing|date=April 5, 2010|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> The opening marked the first time in the college's history that students have the opportunity to live on campus.<ref name="housing">{{cite news|last=Stoll|first=Joe|work=[[WTOL]]|url=http://www.wtol.com/global/story.asp?s=13019517|title=Lourdes College students can now live on campus|date=August 20, 2010|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> Lourdes offers on-campus housing for students at Lourdes Commons. It is located to the South East of the Main Campus. Lourdes Commons offers one and two bedroom apartments with a number of amenities in four separate residence halls.<ref name="housing"/> Student enrollment reached a new record of 2,616 students. In 2011 the college will begin another partnership, with [[Owens Community College]]. Students will be able to earn to earn Bachelor of Science four-year degrees in eight business majors: accounting, finance, business administration, health care administration, human resource management, integrated business, marketing and management, taking the majority of classes at College Hall on the Owens Toledo campus with classes taught by Lourdes faculty.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gibb|first=Emily|work=[[Toledo Free Press]]|url=http://www.toledofreepress.com/2011/03/10/owens-students-can-earn-lourdes-business-degrees/|title=Owens students can earn Lourdes business degrees|date=March 10, 2010|accessdate=June 12, 2011}}</ref>

== Campus == 
{{expand section}}
The campus of Lourdes College is located in [[Sylvania, Ohio]], northwest of [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] less than a mile from the Ohio-[[Michigan]] border on wooded {{convert|89|acre|km2|}} bounded by the [[Ottawa River (Lake Erie)|Ottawa River]] to the north, Silica Drive to the west, Convent Road to the south and a [[Branch line|branch]] of the [[Norfolk Southern Railroad]] to the east.<ref name="tour">{{cite web|work=Lourdes College|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/tour.aspx|title=Virtual Tour|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>

== Academics == 
The university is classified as a [[Masters university|Master<U+2019>s college and university]] by the [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education]].<ref name="carnegie"/> The college utilizes a semester-based academic calendar and has a student-faculty ratio of 11:1.<ref name="usnwr">{{cite web|work=[[US News and World Report]]|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/lourdes-college-3069|title=Lourdes College - Best Colleges - Education|date=August 20, 2010|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> Lourdes College offers 35 undergraduate majors, 6 graduate program, and 9 pre-professional programs and confers degrees from its four schools:<ref>{{cite web|work=Lourdes College|url=http://www.lourdes.edu/MajorsPrograms.aspx|title=Academics: Majors and Programs|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> 
* School of Arts and Sciences
* School of Nursing
* School of Professional Studies
* The Graduate School

Lourdes College's undergraduate programs were not ranked by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' for the 2010-11 academic year,<ref name="usnwr"/> however the Lourdes College School of Nursing was ranked #234 in the top nursing graduate programs.<ref name="usnwrgrad">{{cite web|work=[[US News and World Report]]|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-health-schools/lourdes-college-203757|title=Lourdes College - Best Colleges - Grad School - Nursing|date=August 20, 2010|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> The college has full accreditation from the [[Higher Learning Commission]] (HLC) of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]].<ref name="ncahlc">{{cite web|work=The Higher Learning Commission|url=http://www.ncahlc.org/component/option,com_directory/Action,ShowBasic/Itemid,184/instid,1569/lang,en/|title=Directory of HLC Institutions - Lourdes College|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> Lourdes has been fully accredited by the North Central Association of the Higher Learning Commission since 1964 and received its ten-year renewal in 2006-07.<ref name="ncahlc"/>

== Athletics ==
Lourdes began its athletic program in the fall of 2010 and began competing in men<U+2019>s and women<U+2019>s golf, women<U+2019>s volleyball and men<U+2019>s basketball. The college plans to add additional sports in the following academic years. Lourdes athletics teams are known as the Gray Wolves. The mascot and nickname are closely tied to the story of [[St. Francis of Assisi]] and the [http://www.lourdes.edu/AboutLourdes/MissionMinistry/CampusMiniTour.aspx#wolfOfGubbio Wolf of Gubbio]. Their athletics colors are terracotta, black and white. Recently, Lourdes was named as one of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) newest members. Lourdes recently became the newest member of the [[Wolverine-Hoosier Athletic Conference]] (WHAC) alongside eight other teams from [[Indiana]], [[Michigan]], and [[Ohio]].<ref name="whac"/>

Lourdes athletic teams include:
